<h1>From James Innes</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Dr Sir</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Camp Moun[t] Pleasant [Md.] 27th Septr 1754</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>Your favour of the 22d from Alexa. I recd &amp; shoud be extreamly glade to see you at Winchester, was it any way consistant with my situation to leave this without orders, with which youll please aquaint Major Carlyle and that he would forgive me for not writing to him for I realy have not the time without delaying the Express, if the Governr hath orderd your Regiment here it would be very imprudent in me to Countermand them Especialy as I expect Governr Sharp with his Forces very soon and tho it be now turning towards Winter I would propose the doing something to forward the Service in the Spring.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-01-02-0105-fn-0001" id="GEWN-02-01-02-0105-fn-0001-ptr">1</a> I have with great difficulty labourd hard and only with a few Tools found in this neighbourghood brought in from the Meadows<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-01-02-0105-fn-0002" id="GEWN-02-01-02-0105-fn-0002-ptr">2</a> on which I seized. I have erected a Puntion Fort which when Compleated must of Course be of good Service in this part of the Province, as well as to the present Expedition.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-01-02-0105-fn-0003" id="GEWN-02-01-02-0105-fn-0003-ptr">3</a> notwithstanding when Governr Sharp<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-01-02-0105-fn-0004" id="GEWN-02-01-02-0105-fn-0004-ptr">4</a> and you join us I propose if we agree to goe thirty miles or more to the Westward to do something of the same kind there, tho by last nights advice I have Account the French have gatherd three Hundred Indians to their Fort, since Mr Lyon my Messinger came from that, which was the 21st Curtt[.]<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-01-02-0105-fn-0005" id="GEWN-02-01-02-0105-fn-0005-ptr">5</a> To what purpose these Indians are I know not, but if to pay us a visit. I should be Glad of Your good Company. I observe what you write in regard to Ranking with His Majestys Troops and I do assure you they are they same with me, and now afresh as Captain Rutherford is arrived with respect to my Commission from Governr Dinwiddie. but my Commission from His Majesty being the Oldest leaves no room to cavil so all that subsides and tho. I have the Command with the greatest harmoney.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-01-02-0105-fn-0006" id="GEWN-02-01-02-0105-fn-0006-ptr">6</a> as things are Circumstanced at present I undergoe Fatigue. Plagued &amp; Continualy harrassed in that station more then if otherways, to all which I freely submitt tho not for any obligation the Commitee hath layd upon me. as I have the present service at heart and would do anything in my
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-01-02-pb-0213">[213]</span>
Power to help the opperation of every Part, that you should do duty seperatly and live in good harmonie untill His Majestys Pleasure is known I will take the labouring our<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-01-02-0105-fn-0007" id="GEWN-02-01-02-0105-fn-0007-ptr">7</a> upon myself do double duty by giving out seperate orders, if any better expedient can be found shall be very ready to concur. poor Capt. Stobo is sent to Mount Real and will be kept there till he is exchanged, the Chiefest Reason I can give for this, I am afraid as he wrote two Letters to You and them Letters were opend at Mr Croughans and to Publickly Spoke of and handed aboute the Knowledge thereof came to the Commanding Officers knowledge, and he is strongly watchd ever since, so that the woud not so much as let Mr Lyon see him,<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-01-02-0105-fn-0008" id="GEWN-02-01-02-0105-fn-0008-ptr">8</a> I am sorry to hear many of Your People are sick but thank God we are all well here and live in Cover, only I am obliged to spare some of my Rum as we want Spirits as the cold weather comes on. I am with my Complimtts to all Friends Dr Sir Yor most Humble Servtt</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">James Innes</p>
</div>
<div class="postscript">
<p>P.S. Mr Splidolph wrote me a letter some time agoe about His Commission I have no objection please Aquaintt him. Your Recommendation will be sufficient for him to Act untill he arrives hear when he will certainly have one if you appoint him.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-01-02-0105-fn-0009" id="GEWN-02-01-02-0105-fn-0009-ptr">9</a></p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-02-01-02-0105-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Letter Signed: a letter not in the authors handwriting, but signed by the author ]">LS</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.
 This was addressed to GW at Winchester. Although Mount Pleasant was the name of the camp for the troops under Inness command at Wills Creek during the fall of 1754, the name was seldom used, contemporaries usually referring either to the camp at Wills Creek or merely to the camp.</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-01-02-0105-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-02-01-02-0105-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>Apparently GW wrote Innes after receiving Dinwiddies letter of 11 Sept. 1754 ordering him and his troops to join Innes at Wills Creek. The meeting with Innes at Winchester may have been proposed by GW to settle on a response to Dinwiddies orders, with which GW clearly did not agree. In July the Maryland Assembly authorized 6,000 for military expenses against the French, and Gov. Horatio Sharpe set about raising a company. When he heard that Dinwiddies supply bill did not survive the September meeting of the Virginia Assembly, Sharpe declined compleating the Maryland company but did send the 50 men already raised to Wills Creek (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;i&gt;Archives of Maryland&lt;/i&gt;. 72 vols. Baltimore, 18831972. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Md. Archives</span></span>, 6:99).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-01-02-0105-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-02-01-02-0105-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>Great Meadows.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-01-02-0105-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-02-01-02-0105-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>Puntion is an obsolete form of puncheon. On 16 Oct. George Croghan wrote: Colonel Innis has Built a Fortification at the Mouth of Wills Creek . . . called Fort Mount Pleasant (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;i&gt;Colonial Records of Pennsylvania&lt;/i&gt;. 16 vols. Harrisburg, 184053. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Pa. Arch., Col. Rec.</span></span>, 6:180). On 16 Nov. Dinwiddie wrote to Lord Halifax: The Fort &amp; Magazine . . . are finishd (<span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Virginia Historical Society, Richmond ]">ViHi</span>:
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-01-02-pb-0214">[214]</span>
Dinwiddie Papers). In early December Sharpe described the fortification as an exceedingly small Stoccado Fort built on a poorly chosen location and ordered his Maryland company to begin construction of a larger fort on an adjacent &amp; more elevated piece of Ground (Sharpe to Dinwiddie, 10 Dec. 1754, in <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ William Hand Browne, ed. &lt;i&gt;Correspondence of Governor Horatio Sharpe&lt;/i&gt;. 3 vols. &lt;i&gt;Archives of Maryland&lt;/i&gt;, vols. 6, 9, and 14. Baltimore, 188895. ]">Browne, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Sharpe Correspondence</span></span>, 1:136).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-01-02-0105-fn-0004-ptr" id="GEWN-02-01-02-0105-fn-0004">4</a>

   <p>On 18 Sept. Dinwiddie wrote to Innes: You, probably may see the Govr of Myld the Beginning of next Mo[nth] (<span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Virginia Historical Society, Richmond ]">ViHi</span>: Dinwiddie Papers).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-01-02-0105-fn-0005-ptr" id="GEWN-02-01-02-0105-fn-0005">5</a>

   <p>Colonel Innes had recently sent Lt. Louis Charles Lyon to Contrecoeur at Fort Duquesne with a letter offering to exchange a French officer and two cadets for captains Robert Stobo and Jacob Van Braam of the Virginia Regiment, who were being held hostage at the fort. See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-01-02-0098&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-01-02-0098-fn-0001#GEWN-02-01-02-0098-fn-0001" class="document">William Fairfax to GW, 5 Sept. 1754, n.1</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-01-02-0105-fn-0006-ptr" id="GEWN-02-01-02-0105-fn-0006">6</a>

   <p>By virtue of their royal commissions, James Mackay and Thomas Clarke, captains of the independent companies, refused to obey commands from GW, whose commission as colonel was from Dinwiddie.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-01-02-0105-fn-0007-ptr" id="GEWN-02-01-02-0105-fn-0007">7</a>

   <p>To take the labouring our [oar] was to do the greatest part of the job.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-01-02-0105-fn-0008-ptr" id="GEWN-02-01-02-0105-fn-0008">8</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-01-02-0098&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-01-02-0098-fn-0001#GEWN-02-01-02-0098-fn-0001" class="document">William Fairfax to GW, 5 Sept. 1754, n.1</a>, for the details about Robert Stobos letters and his captivity.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-01-02-0105-fn-0009-ptr" id="GEWN-02-01-02-0105-fn-0009">9</a>

   <p>Carolus de Spiltdorf received a commission as lieutenant effective 29 Oct. 1754.</p>

</div>
</div>
